## Announcing Release v5.0.0 📢 
https://github.com/macrocosm-os/pretraining/tree/v5.0.0

We are excited to announce Release v5.0.0  🎉 . This is a major release that enables native support for multi-dataset evaluation as well as support for more evaluation task types using EvalTasks introduced in taoverse==1.3.7. This will unlock more flexibility in data mixing and more diversity in training tasks in future releases.

Here is  a complete list  of changes:

**1. Native support for multi-dataset evaluation**
Immediate effect

We implemented support for multi-dataset evaluation for all competitions using EvalTask from taoverse 1.3.7. The current 14B-star competition (with multi-dataset evaluation) was initially implemented as an experiment on top of  the 14B (FineWeb-edu2) competition. 
We have recently seen that the winning model of the 14B-star competition was able to surpass the 14B's winner in terms of performance on SOTA benchmarks (Stay tuned for a new blogpost on this in the coming days). This shows that data mixing is quite effective in pushing the performance closer to SOTA. This new release, enables all competitions to have their own data mix (see below).

**2. Updating the data mix**
Activation block: `4_732_978`

Both 3B and 14B will now be evaluated on the following mix:
- HuggingFaceFW/fineweb (30%)
- HuggingFaceFW/fineweb-edu-score-2 (25%)
- bigcode/the-stack-v2-dedup (35%)
- laion/pes2ox-fulltext (5%)
- HuggingFaceTB/FineMath:finemath-3plus (3%)
- HuggingFaceTB/FineMath:infiwebmath-3plus (2%)

Notice that the 14B* will be retired and replaced by the multi-dataset 14B with the above mix at that activation block. All existing submissions for both 14B and 14B-star will continue to be evaluated on the new multi-dataset 14B.

**3. New epsilon lower bounds and decay intervals**
Activation block `4_732_978`

The epsilon decay interval and bounds will be updated for all competitions as follows:

- 3B competition:
Updated:  decays from 0.005 to 0.0002 over 4 days
Updated:  decays from 0.005 to 0.0005 over 7 days

- 14B competition:
Updated:  decays from 0.005 to 0.0002 over 5 days
Updated:  decays from 0.005 to 0.0005 over 10 days

The improvement margin given the new data mix is wider, raising the lower bound of epsilon will ensure higher gains on model losses with each submission. However, we will be closely be monitoring and updating those values as the competition goes.

**4. Updated emission distribution for competitions**
Activation block `4_732_978`

- 3B → 30%
- 14B → 70%

**Other updates**
- Improved weight setting by spinning out separate threads that use different subtensors.
- Switched from bt.logging to taoverse.logging.

**The purpose of this subnet is to collaboratively train the largest LLMs that have ever been created on a decentralized network. **

**We are launching with a 15B model, split across 5 layers.** This means that all miners on the network will be training a chunk of the model of around 5B parameters in size. We highly recommend that both miners and validators use A100s with 80GB VRAM in this first version, since it will comfortably fit the model and optimizer states. You should ensure that your servers have high speed internet connections as this is crucial for your success on the network.
In the coming weeks we will carry out a series of warm-up experiments focused on improving stability, scalability and incentive hardening. Then we will train our first model to convergence. This means that we will periodically restart the training run as we make improvements to the design:

**Stability** — tune system hyperparameters to maintain consistently high throughput, good convergence and optimal weight syncing cadence.
**Scalability** — improve compression rates to reduce network latencies, both for activation processing and weight merging.
**Incentive hardening** — tighten the reward mechanism to ensure that the system rewards miners fairly based on their contribution.

As we stabilize the network, we will add more layers and allow miners to run smaller sections of the model (down to individual layers of 1-2B parameters, requiring 16-24 GB VRAM). This reduces hardware requirements for the network without impacting the model size that we can train on the network, further opening participation. Additionally, we will be enabling miners with powerful machines to run multiple layers on their servers, creating an additional axis for competition and innovation.
This will speed up training, lower the barrier to entry on the network and allow us to expand the network without increasing the hardware requirements for everyone. This is the path to training very, very large models.

## How does it work?

## Mining
**Joining the network** - When miners join the network they will register with the orchestrator using their api client, which will assign them to a layer. There will be up to 50 miners per layer. Miners will download the current global weights for their layer and begin processing activations.
**Activations** - There are two kinds of activation; forwards and backwards. Forwards activations propagate samples through the model to produce losses, and backwards activations propagate the samples in the opposite direction to produce gradients for training their layer weights. Miners will poll the orchestrator for activations using their api client, and will receive anonymized presigned urls which point to an s3 bucket. They then download the activations, locally process them using their model shard and then re-upload their outputs. If a miner fails to process an activation that it has been assigned, it is penalized. This is like an assembly line, where workers pass between adjacent stages in the process. An important part of the design is that samples propagate through the pipeline in random and stochastic paths.
Backwards activations are given precedence over forwards activations as they provide the learning signal. Activation processing happens in all layers at once, but miners process samples and train asynchronously. Miners must process as many activations as possible in each epoch — their score is based on throughput.

**Merging** - Once the orchestrator signals that enough samples have been processed in the network, the state of the system changes from training mode to merging mode. In merging mode, the miners perform a multi-stage process which is a modified version of Butterfly All-Reduce. First, they upload their local weights and optimizer states to the s3 bucket. Then, they are assigned a set of random weight partitions. Importantly, multiple miners are assigned to the same partitions which provides redundant measurement of results for improved fault tolerance and robustness. Miners then must download their partitions, perform a local merge (currently the element-wise geometric mean) and then upload their merged partitions. This design is tolerant to miner failures, so merging is not blocked if some miners do not successfully complete this stage. Finally, miners download the complete set of merged weights and optimizer states. The merging stage is currently the slowest, so we amortize this by running the training stage for longer and effectively training on larger batch sizes.
Once merging is complete, the orchestrator state returns to training mode and the miners continue processing activations. The miners cycle between training mode and merging mode in perpetuity.
## Validating

**Joining the network** - When validators join the network they will register with the orchestrator using their api client. 
**Shadowing miners** - Validators will periodically reproduce an epoch’s worth of work of a randomly selected miner. This can take up to an hour per miner in the current version, and we will reduce this as one of our first priorities post-launch. This is why there is an important tradeoff between effective batch size and network stability. Validators have more work to reproduce when scoring a miner the longer the training stage is. We will soon integrate CLASP into the system to allow the validators to estimate miner contributions using an auditor-like mechanism, but for now we have more basic and hopefully robust approach which is reproducibility checks. Once a validator has checked that all activations were correctly processed by a miner it then performs a local all-reduce to compare its local weights and optimizer state with what the miner uploaded. If a miner passes the check it ‘banks’ a score equal to the total number of activations it processed in that interval.
**Setting weights** - Validators share information via the orchestrator by design. This means that validators submit the miner scores that they produce in their spot check, and all the miner scores are pooled together to give a total consensus score. Periodically, validators request the miner scores from the orchestrator, normalize and set weights. This guarantees that validators agree with each other, sustaining very high validator trust.

## Roadmap

The coming weeks are going to be very busy for us. We will do our best to combat zero day issues while still pushing on our compression research and incentive improvements. To add a bit more color to the exciting research pathways we’re on:
- Reducing merge-related bottlenecks by leveraging our butterfly all-reduce technique

- Bringing CLASP into the incentive mechanism. We will start collecting mainnet data on the results starting from today, and it will go out in the next few weeks. 

We will share the official roadmap next week on novelty search. Stay tuned for the big picture.

Of course, the biggest and most important thing in our roadmap is that we will begin our end-to-end training run once everything is stable. 

We hope that the community can come together around this exciting experiment and work with us to **build the biggest decentralized models the world has ever seen**.
